In the home of Victor-Gadbois, in cooperation with a group of volunteers, body care is provided with the help of nutrition.
That's what palliative care looks like when there's nothing else to do.
To make death more comfortable.
In Quebec, there is one bed of palliative care for 11,700 inhabitants.
That's very little if we realize we're all gonna die someday.
Here life continues in optimal conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the doctors in the home.
Whether it's a level of physical, emotional, or spiritual comfort.
For example, when a person dies, he can be given a sip of brandy or pepsi, according to taste.
Diabetic patients no longer need to monitor their blood sugar levels.
And death is a part of everyday life here.
Last night, they were carrying a beer to Mr. X, who died later last night.
This morning, his son will finish his beer in honor of his late father.
"We help patients as well as their loved ones," says Nathalie Savardová, director of nursing services.
In Victor-Gadbois' home, days go by days, but they don't look like each other.
In addition to the 39 - year - old man who rejoices in his last encounter with his family well - founded on pillows while toasting him in his honor, a tragically 36 - year - old man surrounded by his parents, wife, and two young children dies after trying out all the opportunities to survive.
"For six months there are always three to five beds, which are intended for people with cancer under the age of 45," says Dr. Christiane Martel, concerned.
53% of the patients who come to home Victor-Gadbois come here from their homes, 47% from hospitals.
Problems with access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians simply do not have access to palliative care, i.e. to care that is designed to alleviate suffering once the sick reach the final stage of their lives, whether it is at home, in a hospital or in a nursing home.
And several organizations, such as the home of Victor-Gadbois and the Society for Home Palliative Treatment of Grand Montréal, specialize more or less exclusively in the care provided to cancer patients.
And it is this fundamental unavailability of healthcare in Quebec that causes a number of doctors specializing in palliative care to fear the adoption of a law on euthanasia and assisted suicide.
Since October, the manifesto has been in circulation, signed by peaks in the field of palliative treatment, such as Dr Balfour Mount and Dr Bernard Lapointe, in which they demonstrate their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, the quebe medical system is not powerful enough to provide access for all persons to high-quality palliative care before it is possible to agree to euthanasia.
As she says, she recently experienced a patient who spent 14 days in an emergency room in great pain without anyone taking the necessary steps to relieve her.
They are concerned that patients should not be asked to be killed because they are not adequately cared for.
At the same time, many oncologists care for their patients until the last few moments, regardless of adverse prognosis.
Hélène Richard's chances of survival were already minimal when she left the difficult chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was quitting treatment, she replied that she was sorry that I stopped fighting, she told us.
And she told me it was over!
There is no omnipotent care
Dr. Martel estimates that 90% of patients who wish to die thank their treating physicians for not fulfilling their wishes when the palliative cunt team eased their pain.
It must be said, though, that palliative care is certainly not all-powerful in the treatment of pain.
According to Elsie Monereau, director of palliative care in the Society for Home Palliative Care of Grand Montréal, patients are prevented from treating pain in 8% of cases.
At the very end of life, doctors often use palliative sedatives that put the patient to sleep until the moment of death, whether in shock or whether given permanently.
We can't pretend to ignore this part of the suffering.
A patient we can't relieve of pain will still have more and more access to palliative sedatives.
Sick people who are not given a sedative always say the same thing: "I want to die".
But that doesn't necessarily mean "I want you to give me euthanasia", it means "I want you to relieve my pain."
