And yet the European Central Bank (ECB) is interested in this in its report on virtual finance, which was published in October.
Bitcoin calls "the most successful virtual money", "competitive dollar and euro" and "a period of ordinary money".
Bitcoin differs from other types of virtual money by being like "credits" used to advance in a video game that can be acquired by a game or bought (and sometimes exchanged back).
Facebook's social network also developed a similar system.
Each month, however, the central authority checks and processes individual communications.
In the case of Bitcoin, all network nodes are depositories of the current account book, controllers, money issuers and buyers as well as sellers.
How does this network work?
Each transaction between two users actually takes place between two e-mail addresses.
However, the user may choose a different address for each payment, thereby ensuring anonymity.
The set of information related to this transaction is electronically signed by a double-key encryption system.
The network can thus verify the validity of the transaction.
Thanks to the file content, it is also possible to ensure that exchanged bitcoins exist in the public book of current accounts distributed throughout the network.
The key phase is to write this new transaction into this book.
It is done by solving the mathematical task assigned to computers, whose solver, a temporary central banker, will have the right to complete this additional line.
This is a stage of file cutting; i.e. the transformation of a huge file into a shorter and unique digital print.
Computers "take over" this new transaction and add a number to it, only then they "cut" the whole.
The aim is to find a number that provides a specific print (a lot of zeros at the beginning).
Once this number is found, the other nodes can easily check its accuracy.
The transaction is then indestructibly displayed connected to the string of all other transactions; any modification would change the print.
If the user wanted to pay double of the same money very quickly in a row (within ten minutes), the network will only confirm one of both transactions - the other will be abandoned because each of them has a different print.
The computer that solves the challenge wins 50 bitcoins.
In order to avoid inflation, this remuneration is regularly divided by two, probably by the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is limited by 21 million, but it can be divided into 100 millionths, so there is room for margin...
The difficulty of the given task also increases with increasing level of calculation.
The network has seen its ups and downs.
The websites that provide services for Bitcoin have been attacked and stored bitcoins have been stolen.
"The used loophole does not concern the protocol itself," assures Pierre Noizat, who founded Paymium, a real-money company that uses the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also controls the possibilities for money laundering through this anonymous service.
But this problem also applies to cash.
Important players like Wikipedia reject gifts of this nature.
Others, like a WordPress blog platform, accept them.
Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron of the Weizmann Institute in Israel recently analyzed the current account book and proved that almost 80% of bitcoins are not running.
In November, "big discounts" were launched.
"The $30,000 has been exchanged," rejoices Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul to transform bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, who is also the author of the pedagogical book on this money, has great confidence in the potential of this technology as a transactional network.
His system, Paytunia, is equivalent to a credit card (with real money) or non-contact cell phone payment, but uses Bitcoin to verify transactions, which makes it cheaper.
Moreover, the wearer manages his identity and can remain anonymous.
The system is easy to set for traders where there is no need to install new terminals or software.
Just give an address that can be "photographed and identified" by the phone, explains Pierre Noizat, who assures that he already has thousands of users.
There is a general movement to question hierarchical systems and to move towards more horizontal systems.
"It will be a while before Bitcoin succeeds, but 2013 could be decisive," he predicts.
Moreover, in its report, the ECB expects a reassessment of the various risks considered to be increased today if this type of money is successful.
