Difficult Work at the Egyptian Constitution
President Muhammad Morsi embarked on another game of poker.
While Egypt remains the most divided in its history because of the constitution, which temporarily grants it unlimited powers, it has decided to play vabank.
On Wednesday, he announced, regardless of the opinion of everyone else, that the Constitutional Assembly would approve the final text tomorrow.
Less than a week ago, the head of state granted this assembly two more months to complete the necessary work.
For almost two years, Egypt has been using a provisional text that has been supplemented many times, weakening the country’s constitutional stability and leading to legal speculation.
This new initiative has only further strengthened the country’s diversity.
From the opposition's point of view, the President remains in his 'autocrat delirium', continues to 'broke his word' and 'stamp the law'.
However, its supporters assure that it is a means of turning the constitutional and political crisis as quickly as possible and speeding up the transition process.
There should be a referendum in two weeks.
This is a very short period of time that will force the Brotherhood to withdraw from the purpose of explaining the article to the Egyptians.
For the President, it is also a way to regain national and democratic legitimacy, while the whole country is wreaking havoc.
As he confirmed in an interview for the American weekly Time, Muhammad Morsi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote in favour.
Especially because this hastily organised vote puts the Egyptian people in front of the ultimatum: 'You will either approve my text or I will retain unlimited powers', which should otherwise end after the adoption of the new constitution.
And in this particular climate yesterday, 85 Members of the said Constitutional Assembly approved the text with a large majority of Islamists.
Most liberals were absent in the vote.
In mid-November, not long before the constitution was announced, they slammed the door saying they didn't have a chance to assert their views.
The defenders of human rights, civil society, or members of religious minorities imitated their actions.
In order to achieve the quorum, 11 alternates were quickly added yesterday morning.
Some of them are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
It is not surprising, then, that the articles of the Constitution were often voted unanimously.
The commentators continued to consider that one of the few disputes revolved around that day... an hour for prayer, when some members of the committee felt that the hours in the meeting room were not properly adjusted.
The text voted on last night consists of 234 articles.
The subject matter of general attention, Article 2, ultimately remains identical to the 1971 version of the Constitution and states that "the Sharia Law principles are the main source of law".
Salafist parties, for whom the introduction of Islamic law is one of the fundamental requirements, hoped to replace the term 'principles' with the term 'rules', which would allow for stricter application.
For Islamists, the fact that this article has not been corrected represents a sign of their goodwill and respect for other parts of Egyptian society.
"Physicism," the liberals object, who see it as a rhetorical problem.
According to them, the Islamization of the Constitution is carried out through other articles.
They shall focus in particular on Article 220, which confers an advisory role on the University of Al-Azhar, in particular on matters of compliance with Sharia law.
According to the expert on Egypt, Sophie Pommier, this is disturbing, because "persons called to express themselves are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
It can be seen as the beginnings of theocracy".
The fear of liberals is even more fueled by the fact that the next president of the university should be less moderate than the current one.
"For now, there has been no concrete religious consequence.
With this constitution, Egypt remains a framework civil state.
Most of the lawyers who worked on this text are not Ulamians, but university workers, many of whom have studied in French schools," said Alexis Blouet, who prepares work on the constitutional transition in Egypt.
However, they agree that "there may be contradictions regarding the interpretation of Article 220 because the terms used in it belong to the religious dictionary.
In particular, there is a reference to "fiqh" [Islamic legal science, note red.]
And in the future, there may be a question of how competent civil judges are to be able to comment on this."
Yesterday's approved text is, in addition to the religious pages, highly criticized because of the extended powers granted to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood insists that there has been a significant restriction against the former regime.
Another disputed place: the powers vested in the army.
In accordance with the wishes of military officials, verification of the defence budget will not be carried out by Parliament, but by the National Defence Council.
Furthermore, proceedings with civilians will not be banned in military courts, as the Human Rights Association has requested.
These associations are talking about their doubts in relation to the text that they believe is directed against freedom.
The crime of blasphemy is maintained and the insult is still banned, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, especially for the press.
Moreover, no article deals with the protection of women, emphasizes Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
In its view, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture referred to in Article 36.
That word was not mentioned in the previous constitution.
While the president of Egypt was scheduled to perform in a television speech last night, manifestations are scheduled for this afternoon.
The supporters of the head of state will then show up on Saturday.
