Liberally oriented economic systems in the EU as well as in a globalised world are based on the principle of more, unregulated competition.
In its effect, this means that individual economic units, national economic systems, stand in a permanent conflict among themselves.
This is due to the principle of free trade and free, unlimited movement of private capital, along with unbridled financial speculation.
Due to significant differences in labour prices, (major) price tensions occur.
Under that term, it is necessary to understand the situation in which the producer is trying to compete with the imports of cheap goods by "inducing" the price of the competitor in order to bring down more market share and thereby increase its own profits.
On a mass scale, this means either transferring production abroad or buying or dying there.The result is high unemployment in countries where labour prices are high compared to other economies.
Since private capital has no social responsibility and thus the responsibility for unemployment produced by it, the social costs of the state are necessarily increasing.
