The problem is that it was defined and discussed in many different ways, said John D. Eastwood, professor of psychology at York University in Ontario, Canada.
After looking at the research literature and presenting the idea to the target group of about 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues defined boredom as an experience "I wanted to do something that would satisfy me, but I was not able to do it."
Boring is different from apathy by not being involved in anything, but wanting to be.
He says there's no urge to do anything about apathy.
He says that the core of boredom is "disturbing the process of attention associated with a bad mood and a feeling of slow passing time."
Boring can be a lot like depression.
But Professor Eastwood said that while they can have a relationship with each other, boring people tend to see a problem like the environment or the world, while people who are depressed see a problem in themselves.
Sometimes we think we're bored when we're just having trouble concentrating.
In his study "The Unengaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention", published in September in the journal Perspectives on Psychological Science, Professor Eastwood, and his colleagues pointed out an earlier experiment in which participants listened to the tape on which a person read an article from the magazine.
Some groups heard a loud and unrelated television program in the next room, others heard it so quietly that they barely noticed it, while the third group did not hear it at all.
Those who heard the television program silently reported more boredom than the other two groups - they had difficulty concentrating, but they were not sure why and attributed these problems to boredom.
When you try to concentrate on a difficult or engaging task, distractions can lead to boredom, said Mark J. Fenske, professor of neuroscience at the University of Guelph in Ontario and one of the authors of the study.
On the other hand, when you do something boring, "like finding the wrong parts on the factory line, distracting music can help you not to get bored."
In fact, he said, now we know that twisting and doodleing, which is often seen as a sign of boredom, can actually help with boredom to fight and keep people physically more attentive.
"The research shows that children who are allowed to wiggle will learn more and retain more information than those who are forced to sit still," said Professor Fenske.
We've all experienced boredom at times - the delay of my flight, the roaring speaker, especially the lengthy movie.
But some individuals have a better chance of being bored than others.
To help measure boredom, scientists in the 1980’s developed a “Stip for Boring Vulnerability” (Bordom Proneness Scale).
The scale includes questions like: "Many things I have to do are repeated and monotonous," and "I have so many interests that I don't have time to do them all."
Using these scales scientists found that boys tend to get bored more often than girls, said Stephen Vodanovich, professor of psychology at the University of West Florida, especially when it comes to the need to have more and different external stimulations.
Teenagers, however, are generally indifferent.
In 1991 Reed Larson, professor of human and social development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he contacted nearly 400 teenagers and their parents seven to eight times a day.
He found that 32 percent of teenagers reported being bored at school and doing homework, while 23 percent reported being bored when they were away from school.
On the other hand, 3 percent of parents said they were bored.
Professor Larson stated that he did not know whether the percentage of boredom would now, 21 years later, be higher or lower.
But he said that he knew that "adolescents are the peak time for boredom", which is largely due to the fact that children and youth are not given much control over what they want to do.
So back to my original question, "Is boredom good for you?"
As research shows, sometimes not, because in its extreme form it can lead people to take absurd physical risks, gamble, or abuse addictive substances as a way to alleviate them.
On the other hand, many philosophers and writers discussed the connection between boredom and creativity, said Professor Vodenovich, who had studied the problem for more than two decades.
"Nude is a way of telling you that you should do something else," said Gary Marcus, professor of psychology at NYU.
But the brain doesn't always know the best thing to do.
If you are bored and use this energy to play guitar and cook, it will make you happy.
But if you watch TV, it will only make you happy for a while, not for a long time.
So if your child is bored and you give him an iPad, he won't be bored anymore, but he won't learn how to entertain himself or drive himself, said Professor Fenske.
And "this separate procedure is transferred from one situation to another," said the professor.
Your child will not only learn how to entertain himself, but will gain greater self - control in other areas.
I don't think we really want to celebrate boredom.
But we shouldn't be too critical of her either.
Rather, our goal should be to feel comfortable when we are out of the reach of constant grinding activity and technology.
Professor Eastwood agreed.
"We accuse her of the need to be bored even more, but boredom is a painful, restless desire to be connected to something meaningful," he said.
What people are actually looking for, he said, is a way to relax and enjoy free time.
"In an environment in which we are constantly overstimulated," he said, "it's hard to find ways to entertain ourselves when the noise turns off."
