Petronella Wyatt: "I was forced to leave Oxford because I'm a conservative."
Today's university students are not the only ones who are attacked for their opinions.
I don't remember ever dreaming about studying at Oxford University.
Both my father and my older brother studied at the university, which I thought was the world's largest headquarters of knowledge, a modern-style wined Greek symposium motivating two pillars of civilization, free thinking and tolerance.
Meanwhile, in the late 1980 ’ s, within two weeks of taking up Worcester College, where I wanted to study history, I packed my suitcases and rushed into the first scandal of my life.
My father collapsed and wept.
My friends were confused.
The Evening Standard diary said I gave up because I objected to loving students in the next room.
Writer A.N. Wilson exhilarated that I left because I was forced to drink from battered mugs.
The truth was less comical.
I ran away.
Yes, I ran away because I was the subject of systematic bullying and intimidation.
Not because of my somewhat bizarre name or the fact that I came from a private school.
I was persecuted for one reason and in this cradle of supposed enlightenment it was both bigoted and barbaric: my father, the late Woodrow Wyatt, was a high-ranking advisor to Margaret Thatcher and I was a supporter of the Conservative Party.
You may ask why I'm bringing this up now.
Simply because the latest reports suggest that a new generation of students on the right of the center suffer similar persecution.
The institutionalized and growing hatred of conservative students at Oxford is so great that last week, a group of these students sought equal rights protection, such as gays, people with disabilities, and ethnic minorities.
Conservative members of the younger class association (JCR) at Corpus Christi College claim that because of their political views, "often they are actively isolated, exposed to personal attacks and are shown not to be welcome".
They call for a position to be established in the University Equal Opportunities Committee to ensure that they can freely communicate their views.
Their situation was not helped by the recently mentioned BBC Two TV documentary, entitled Wonderland: Young, Bright and on the Right, about student political events, which he portrayed as freaks and neo-Nazis.
A graduate named Joe Cooke, former president of the Oxford University Conservative Association (OUCA), who rode Rolls-Royce, was dressed in a silver suit and had a cane with a silver head.
At other universities, conservative students say that they are treated as "victim lambs" because of the introduction of higher tuition fees.
Twenty-year-old Luke Black, vice president of Nottingham University Conservative Association, told Sunday's newspaper that "the leftist influence in universities is growing.
People think we're like the Bullingdon Club without even meeting with us."
A 21-year-old history student at Corpus Christi Samuel Roberts, who is behind the movement for greater protection, says that such a climate is 'unpleasant', while the 19-year-old president-elect UUCA Stephanie Cherill says that there has been a deterioration in the access of JCR members to the people on the right of Wednesday.
"This poses a threat to the atmosphere of intellectual debate, as well as to the well-being of members," he says.
During my first few weeks in Oxford, I was a minority of a member.
I got on in September 1986, 18-year-old and crippling in a shy way.
Hatred of the Conservative Party was the hottest.
A year earlier, the university voted to reject the honorary title of former student Margaret Thatcher due to cuts in funding for higher education.
Even Stalinists would tremble with fear from the atmosphere.
During the first few days of the opening week, when new students meet with each other and with professors, I was given a taste of the wormwood that was to come.
I found that not only do professors quietly approve of taunting conservative pupils, but they also enjoy participating.
The policy of the mining strike, privatization and opposition of the government to sanctions against apartheid in South Africa was brought into the wooded auditoriums.
My first lecture concerned the translation of the 18th century French text into English, and I was not prepared for what followed.
"Miss Wyatt," said Professor Harry Pitt (now deceased), "please translate the first paragraph."
I was pretty tough about it.
Professor Pitt, a little man with a face like cake dough, was very biley.
"The Thatchers refuse to learn French, or are they just stupid?" he asked.
The other students giggled.
I had tears in my eyes.
"I suggest you take some basic French lessons in your spare time, unless you are too busy with social matters," said Professor Pitt.
I went back to my room with a broken heart.
At dinner at school, I sat alone when I felt a slight pat on my shoulder.
He was a second year student named James who introduced himself as a member of the UCA.
"I know who you are," he said graciously.
I'm afraid so.
Anyone suspected of conservatism is a target.
It's bad enough for me now, but they know your father's close to Margaret Thatcher, so it's gonna get even worse for you.
Most conservative freshmanes pretend to be Labour.
Later in the local pub, I tried cowardly to pretend.
I insisted that I disagree with everything Thatcher said.
This trick proved unsuccessful.
A first-year student in philosophy, politics and economics who (what irony) went to Eton said, "You are the daughter of a fascist pig."
You're infected.
The other students didn't like him.
I was sick, dirty.
"How do conservatives love each other?" asked one.
He beats each other up, doesn't he?
I felt the way homosexuals must have felt before the liberal legislation of the 1960s.
Could I ever lead a normal life in Oxford?
Would I be forced to meet like - minded people only after dark?
Would I have to turn into a Labourer and suppress my natural tendencies?
For three years, they evolved in front of me as a purgatory of ignorance and isolation.
The only openly conservative professor was Norman Stone, a professor of modern history who lived in my faculty.
He was hated not only for being conservative, but also for being Margaret Thatcher's foreign policy advisor and one of the speakers.
He was barely there.
He hated that place for its provinciality and pettyness and for its tendency to Marxist-Determinist view of history.
In 1997 he took the position of professor at the University of Bilkent in Ankara, Turkey.
"You will not be happy here," he told me.
I began to commute from Oxford to my parents' home in London, seeking refuge with my unbiased metropolitan friends and family.
I told my father I hated Oxford and why.
He couldn't believe it.
During his studies at Oxford in the 1940s, all political views were accepted.
"But it is the best place in the world," he said pathetically.
They wouldn't do that, not in a city of dream moods.
Even my communist friends have always had perfect manners.
His wet eyes were gloomy.
Try it again.
I'm sure it's just a joke.
It would break my heart if you left.
Exhausted by frequent trips to London, my emotional resilience worsened.
My friend, also a supporter of the Conservative Party, succumbed to pressure and gave up his convictions.
The following week in the course of teaching, when another professor of history in absolute seriousness said that I was an "enemy of the people", I decided to do the same.
Even though I blushed inside, I confessed to being brainwashed by my parents and calling them "old fools".
