Hardest craft in the world: Sulphur carriers in Kawah Ijen
For four euros, carriers in the area of the Indonesian volcano gamble with their life and health as they carry 70 kilos of sulphur down steep stone paths.
There are people for whom their work is hell, and there are those who literally work in hell.
This is the case of Anta Wijayi, one of the 400 miners who earn their living by extracting sulphur from Kawah Ijen volcano in the east of the Indonesian island of Java.
Because of this, it must rock every day to the bottom of the crater, where sulphur gases escape from the inside of the Earth and when in contact with the air it goes into a solid state.
After cutting out large blocks of sulfur, which together weigh up to 70 kilos, it carries them on its shoulders in two bamboo baskets along steep stone paths.
It is only 250 metres to the top of the volcano, but it takes over 40 minutes for it to rise at a turtle’s pace because it maintains balance and carefully reconsiders its steps so that it does not slip and fall into the abyss.
They know that any stumbling could cost them their lives, as happened to a French tourist who crashed from Kawah Ijen rocks years ago.
Miners in Kawah Ijen earn five cents for every kilo of sulfur they produce
When they're upstairs, they take a trip around the tourists who photograph them like they're monkeys in a circus, and they're tired of taking the heavy weight baskets that the mining company placed a little bit lower, at an altitude of 1850 meters.
It is a company PT Candi Ngrimbi, which has been mining in the volcano since 1960 and has never paid its workers more than 662 Indonesian rupees (five cents) per kilo of sulphur.
Then it sells it for 10,000 rupees (83 cents) to the petrochemical industry, because this mineral has its place in everyday life and is used for the production of matches, fun pyrotechnics, cosmetics, dynamite and even for the bleaching of sugar.
"Because it is normally 70 kilos, we earn about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) per trip," Anto explains, who usually takes three trips a day.
It takes three hours for one journey and it is destroyed at the end, but it can earn 138,000 rupees (11.5 euros) per day.
Even if it appears to be a negligible amount for such inhuman efforts, it's three times what he would have made in the field.
"The daily wage of miners is very high here. For example, 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) per day are paid for coffee collection, and the salary for two weeks is two million rupees (167 euros)," explains the carrier who previously worked on Bali as a bricklayer.
There was his salary of 75,000 rupees (6.2 euros) per day and the work was not so hard, but Anto returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a village near the volcano, for a serious reason that is as convincing in Indonesia as the sulfur: "I married a young girl from Bali, who is Hindu, and I took her to Java to convert to Islam."
Anto has asthma, he's having trouble breathing, he's still coughing and his eyes are irritated by toxic gases.
At the age of 27, Anto risked his life three times a day in Kawah Ijen volcano, whose sulfur had already begun to take its toll on him, even though his face was protected by a special mask and glasses.
He's got asthma, he's having trouble breathing, he's still coughing, and his eyes are irritated by toxic gases leaking from the volcano.
That's the price he has to pay to achieve his dream.
"I will work for two more years because I want to open a shop or study Spanish or French," he promises more than decent English.
This likable and intelligent young man with fate could be a tourist guide, waiter or receptionist in a hotel, and instead he does the work of a porter.
She shares a dirty wooden hut with other carriers and wakes up at 2:00 a.m. every day because sulphur continues to come out at night and its characteristic yellow colour changes into blue and bright darkness.
Despite the darkness surrounding him, Anto goes into the crater and illuminates the path with a small lamp attached to his helmet and bought it himself with his money.
About 400 carriers on the shoulders of the basket with sulfur from the bottom of the crater
Although the company has high incomes, it has not mismanaged the production of sulphur due to cost savings, nor has it provided any equipment to carriers working on their own and with such efforts.
In fact, they don’t even get a share of 30,000 rupees (EUR 2.5) from the photo supplement, which, along with a ticket for 15,000 rupees (EUR 1.2), is selected by park keepers from tourists arriving to take pictures of the volcano and its human mules.
"This work is for cattle, and not for humans," Madrusin objected, a robust 42-year-old carrier who has been working in Kawah Ijen for three decades since he left school.
He can lift up to 110 kilos and assure us that he can work as long as possible, because he needs money to educate his three sons between the ages of 18 and 10.
I'm not going to retire, I'm going to die here because the volcano was my whole life.
Although sulfur burns the throat and stings in the eyes, when the wind turns unexpectedly and engulfs the miners in dense fumes coming out of the volcano, the miners are so bitter that none of them complains that they suffer from serious diseases... but it is evident from their frequent respiratory problems, arthritis, knee pain and wounds on the shoulders caused by weight baskets.
At the age of 53, an unainic who balances his basket on his back can load only 50 kilos.
Each day he and his colleagues mine 15 tons of sulfur in the volcano, which then three trucks take a steep route between the thicket to a warehouse in Tamansari, 18 kilometers away.
"I will not retire, I will die here because the volcano has been my whole life," Unainik claims and opens wide mouths, where several teeth are missing.
Of his five sons he is the eldest, thirty years old, he also earns from mining sulphur.
Time passes, but the constant misery of one of the most difficult crafts in the world persists from generation to generation - crafts carried out by human mules in Kawah Iljen.
