These changes in social standards have contributed to increasing the number of single people and postponing marriage and childbearing, resulting in a reduction in birth rates in Singapore.
While there were efforts under immigration policy to drastically increase the influx of immigrants as a measure against the decline in population, this has caused displeasure among the local population.
Some Singapore websites show unhidden xenophobia against many new immigrants, especially the Chinese, who are criticized for maintaining low wages and a small effort to integrate.
The increase in immigration is also seen as one of the reasons why last year Singapore’s government party recorded its worst electoral outcome since independence.
After the election, there was an effort to solve the problem through quotas and higher fees for foreign workers.
Unexpected Consequences
While the decline in birth rates has known implications for national economic growth, tax revenues, health spending, and immigration policy, there have also been some unexpected consequences for Singapore.
The government is trying not to build so many small houses.
For example, it began to affect the real estate business.
The Office for Urban Development has begun to regulate the number of small flats known as "boot boxes" that can be built in certain urban zones.
These apartments have an area of 46 square meters and have had a great success in sales.
However, there is a concern that these apartments can support the bachelor lifestyle and discourage developers from building large family houses.
But Lim Yew Soon, CEO of EL Developers, claims that their shoeboxes sell much faster than larger houses.
"They are more popular by selling them days to weeks faster than houses with larger size.
That's why they're much better for our cash flow."
However, it admits that the new standards set clearer rules for developers who were previously limited when they wanted to offer too many small houses in one project.
Too stressed.
Singapore is a city state.
Although these new rules could be aimed at increasing the birth rate of the nation, the conversation with Singapore’s financial district workers in the city centre suggests that they will not have much effect.
"People are always stressed out, houses are expensive, as well as education, so many people postpone it," says the young clerk.
"Let the others have children.
But it is important for me to rely on my own money and time," says another, about 20-year-old, young man.
Men and women refer to careers, stress, and cost of living and education as reasons that prevent them from having children.
So no matter how much the government tries to force citizens to have children, they are the Singaporens who have the last word on starting a family.
What is private offline is both private and online
Privacy.
According to the dictionary published by the Royal Spanish Academy, it is something of a personal nature or "private life area that everyone has the right to protect against any disruption".
What is privacy for a person under the age of 16?
How does he apply this definition in his daily life and social media?
Does he understand the dangers he is exposed to when he publishes things on the Internet that he would most certainly not tell anyone during normal communication?
Journalists from elPeriodico interviewed five boys and girls between 10 and 15 years of age who are frequent Internet users.
In four cases, they considered the concept of privacy to be "something entirely personal" and as "user name and password" when it came to social networks.
"I wouldn't publish my biggest secret," says ten-year-old Jorge in an attempt to explain the importance of privacy in places like Facebook, Twitter, Hotmail and Windows Live Messenger, where he has had accounts for two years.
"They're very secret secrets, my mom may know about them, but not the whole world," she says.
"I put nice pictures or pictures of us playing on FB.
I'm talking to my friends there, too.
I wouldn't share a picture that wasn't mine, or a picture that would mock someone," he says.
This boy realizes that it is wrong to publish obscene photographs, photographs of naked persons or photographs of crimes, or write humiliating or rude comments.
Jorge says he knows all 35 friends he has on FB and his nine Twitter followers.
Most of them are related.
Among them is a mother who has the name and password of one of the accounts.
"I set up a Twitter account to express my opinions and write interesting posts.
I don't know if anyone will answer, I'm just putting them there," he adds.
"Social networks are fun, I can talk to relatives who are far away or quickly communicate with friends," he says.
Without hesitation, he says he would never accept a request from an unknown person.
He wouldn't even care if someone recommended someone unknown to him.
The case of 14-year-old José is different.
This teenager owns accounts on Hotmail, Facebook, My Space and Ask networks and admits that he does not know 20 people from his list of friends.
"I am not afraid because we have something in common, such as music," he says.
According to this boy, none of them were leading him on or asking him for an address or phone number.
"If they push me or demand me, I will simply remove them from my account," he admits.
José applied to Ask after reading his Twitter recommendation.
This boy is not a stranger's experience with what is now called cyberbullying.
"A friend of mine was blackmailed on social media.
They threatened him and asked for money.
He never knew who it was," he confirms.
According to José, the victim didn't check out of the account.
"You just activated a private regime."
Then explains a series of steps to set up the account safely.
Unlike Jorge, this boy would publish photos of acquaintances in awkward or awkward situations.
"Of course I'd do it if someone bothered me or if I just wanted to.
Even though I know it's cyberbullying," he says.
Key questions
Marielos Porrasová, an English teacher and a graduate in the field of Education and Teaching, believes that children and adolescents need to understand that the main objective of these networks is to inform them.
He says: "The Internet was created as a means of finding information, but when social networks appeared, the rules of the game changed."
Marrielos Porras notes that academic worker Marc Prensky, a graduate of education at Yale University and author of the article Digital Aboriginals and Digital Immigrants, introduced these concepts to explain this phenomenon.
"Digital natives are children and young people who were born at the time of this technology.
We are digital immigrants who have to teach them, and yet we are learning ourselves," he says.
It explains that this is a complex topic, 'because we ask them to recognize what is appropriate to spread, publish and say, and what is not, at an age when they are not ready for it'.
Also, to be discreet - as far as the surroundings are concerned - at a time when what they desire most is to be popular, to have thousands of friends and not think about the consequences", he adds.
According to this specialist, the most effective way to show children and adolescents what privacy is, asking questions that make them think.
"Telling them not to do anything doesn't work," he adds.
Next, Marjorie Porras lists some of the possibilities: There are things you wouldn't tell a stranger, so why do you do it on the Internet?
Or, "Would you like someone to post your picture the way you posted your friend's?
You know what other people publish about you?
When you mark the persons in the photos from the celebrations, did you ask these persons for permission?
And one more: does everyone always need to know what you're doing?
The next point is to make them realize that they have to behave in the Internet environment as they do outside of it.
It's the same rules.
"Man is guided by respect, morality and other principles outside the Internet and should be the same on social networks," he says.
Supervision
Estuardo Guardia, university professor, first degree teacher, and educational advisor explains the need for parents to carefully read the rules of social networks.
"If they understand every insidious thing, they have a good basis for talking to their children about the consequences they may have of setting up an account on the Internet.
For example, as regards age or what is allowed to be shared or published," he says.
The Guardia believes that it is crucial to remind children of the traditional rule of 'do not talk to strangers'.
The South American Summit ends and the Declaration of Lima has not been published
The sixth presidential summit of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) held in Peru ended today without the release of the Lima Declaration, which was announced and reportedly signed by the seven presidents present.
Efe has repeatedly attempted to gain access to a document signed at the sixth meeting of the Heads of State and Government of Unasur, but representatives of the Foreign Ministry and the Presidential Office, who at the outset stated that the document would be published after the summit, stated that it would later be published on the Peruvian Government’s website.
They also stated that the content was published by Peruvian President Ollanta Humala in a few brief press statements.
Journalists had limited access to information throughout the summit.
During the meeting, the video from the presidential assembly without sound was broadcast in the press room with the message "confidential meeting, audio transmission prevented".
A small amount of information available to journalists was provided by the press speakers of some governments who were present, but not by the Peruvian spokesman.
The only document published during the negotiations was a list of participating presidents, which led to the disapproval of hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who asked for more information.
Later, the Peruvian presidential office sent an e-mail to the media with a "final statement" from the summit, but it was just a statement from President Humala, not an official document that concluded the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the third summit of the South American and Arab countries (America del Sur-Países Arabes, ASPA) and even on this occasion, the originally promised Lima Declaration was not published, even though the press was eagerly required.
On the official ASPA website you can find out that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities sought to ensure broadcasting for all journalists, but they completely prevented the information from being supplied.
The summit ended, inter alia, with a joint commitment by Chile and Peru to the adoption of a judgment of the Hague Court which addresses the dispute over the border between the two countries.
President Peru Ollanta Humala and President Chile Sebastian Piñera met during a regional meeting and confirmed that they would respect the decision of the International Court of Justice in The Hague, which on Monday will begin hearing the defence speech of both parties to discuss the dispute that Lima initiated against Santiago.
"We will submit and execute a judgment that will resolve the dispute that we are discussing today in this international court," said President Humala, along with his Chilean counterpart.
"Chile has been, is and will be a country respecting international law, peaceful dispute resolution, conventions and international courts," added Piñer and greeted President Humal with a handshake at the flags of both countries.
The confirmation by both presidents that the International Court of Justice was subject to a decision was published after Colombia had adopted the Bogot Pact this week, thereby expressing its submission to the judgments of the international court which decided on the maritime borders with Nicaragua, and Colombia considered this decision to be completely wrong.
The summit took place without the participation of the presidents of Brazil (Dilma Rouseff), Venezuela (Hugo Chávez), Bolivia (Evo Morales) and Argentina (Cristina Kirchner).
Paraguay was expelled from Unasur in 2011 after the withdrawal of then-President Fernando Lug and did not attend the meeting.
The host president, Ollanta Humala, was charged with opening the morning speeches and closing the Lima summit shortly after noon.
The President read the final document in which he reported that 16 agreements were adopted and 31 projects between South American countries were planned, with $17 billion in investments.
In addition to the agreements adopted, he mentioned that UNASUR member countries will take 'important steps towards the goal of South American citizenship for which residence agreements are extended'.
He informed that actions were supported to improve 'cooperation in combating civil uncertainty and international organised crime, to improve the availability of medicines and cheap Internet in all parts of South America and to joint and effective measures against the risks of natural disasters'.
When Europe is in crisis, "it does not have a winning essence (Latin America), but it is intended to expand our productivity and show our nations a better future," Humala added.
"We have decided to give priority to a group of 31 symbolic projects that will improve transport connections between various places in South America, especially rural and border areas... so that our countries can be better connected and create new economic links," said the Peruvian President.
He mentioned that five of these projects concerned Peru and the transverse axes of its territory from coast to Brazil, and the other two concerned a better connection with Ecuador, but did not provide more details.
The final document also touched on the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process in this country will serve to bring it back to the Union of South American Nations", from which it is currently excluded.
Another issue highlighted by the summit was the need for Latin America to remain a prosperous and peaceful area that is whole and has good neighbourly relations.
In this sense, Colombian President Juan Manuel Santos said before attending a regional meeting that he hoped to meet his Nicaraguan counterpart, Daniel Ortega, on Saturday, to discuss with respect the International Court of Justice’s ruling on the dispute over maritime borders, which is being questioned by Bogota.
